{{tooshort|date=October 2018}} {{Infobox person | name = Alexia Arthurs | image = | residence = Jamaica and New York | alma_mater = [[Iowa Writers' Workshop]] | known_for = ''How to Love a Jamaican: Stories'' | website = https://alexiaarthurs.com/ }}
'''Alexia Arthurs''' is a writer who grew up in both Jamaica and the United States of America. She writes about the variability of experiences of black identity of immigrants from African countries, Jamaica, and other countries of the West Indies from recent immigrants to those brought over during slavery. <ref name="interview">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theparisreview.org/blog/2018/08/07/mermaids-and-transgressive-sex-an-interview-with-alexia-arthurs/|title=Mermaids and Transgressive Sex: An Interview with Alexia Arthurs|last=Bereola|first=Abigail|date=2018-08-07|website=The Paris Review|language=en|access-date=2018-10-24}}</ref> Her writings include short stories about community, generations, mermaids, sexuality and more.<ref name="interview"/>
==Life== Arthurs graduated from the [[Iowa Writers' Workshop]].<ref name="Iowa Wins">{{Cite web|url=https://writersworkshop.uiowa.edu/resources/news/alexia-arthurs-wins-plimpton-prize|title=Alexia Arthurs Wins the Plimpton Prize|publisher=Iowa Writers' Workshop|language=en|access-date=2018-07-25}}</ref> was awarded the 2017 ''Paris Review'' [[Plimpton Prize]].<ref name="Iowa Wins" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theparisreview.org/blog/2016/07/06/bad-behavior-an-interview-with-alexia-arthurs/|title="Bad Behavior": An Interview with Alexia Arthurs|last=Love|first=Caitlin|date=2016-07-06|website=The Paris Review|language=en|access-date=2018-07-25}}</ref> Her first book, ''How To Love A Jamaican: Stories'',<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/vb3wva/an-excerpt-from-alexia-arthurs-upcoming-novel-how-to-love-a-jamaican-v24n10|title=A Short Story from Alexia Arthurs's Upcoming Collection, 'How to Love a Jamaican'|date=2017-12-21|work=Vice|access-date=2018-07-25|language=en-us}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://themillions.com/books-reviews/how-to-love-a-jamaican-stories-1524799203|title=The Millions: How to Love a Jamaican: Stories by Alexia Arthurs|website=themillions.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-07-25}}</ref> was published in 2018 and was identified by ''Entertainment Weekly'',<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://ew.com/books/july-2018-books/|title=20 new books to read in July|work=EW.com|access-date=2018-07-25|language=en}}</ref> ''Buzzfeed News'',<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/alexiaarthurs/fiction-being-the-only-queer-woman-at-a-very-straight|title=Fiction: Being The Only Queer Woman At A Very Straight Wedding|work=BuzzFeed News|access-date=2018-07-25|language=en}}</ref> and Bitch Media<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bitchmedia.org/article/bitchreads-july-2018-selections|title=11 Books Feminists Should Read In July|work=Bitch Media|access-date=2018-07-25|language=en}}</ref> as one of the best Summer reads of 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.shondaland.com/inspire/books/a21606538/jamaican-authors-books-literary-renaissance/|title=8 Books by Jamaican Authors Every Person Should Read|date=2018-06-19|work=Shondaland|access-date=2018-07-25|language=en-US}}</ref> Arthurs teaches at the Iowa Writers' Workshop.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://hazlitt.net/feature/its-more-complicated-grass-being-greener-interview-alexia-arthurs|title=‘It’s More Complicated Than the Grass Being Greener’: An Interview with Alexia Arthurs|date=2018-07-24|work=Hazlitt|access-date=2018-07-25}}</ref>
